<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
Violation: the third clause 'off += (size_t) len' uses the object 'len', which is assigned in the loop body (len = read(...)). MISRA C 2023 Rule 14.2 clause 3 requires the third clause to modify only the loop counter and not use objects that are modified in the for-loop body. The first and second clauses are acceptable, but using 'len' (modified in the body) in the third clause violates the rule.
</scenario>

<instruction>
Judge whether the report is correct or not.
</instruction>

explanation:
The report is correct. In the for statement
  for (off = 0; off < sizeof(rand_data); off += (size_t) len)
the third clause uses the object len, but len is assigned in the loop body (len = read(...)). MISRA C 2023 Rule 14.2 clause 3 requires the third clause to modify only the loop counter and not use objects that are modified in the loop body (and the loop body includes the effects of any functions called). Because len is modified in the body, using it in the third clause violates the rule. A straightforward fix is to make the third clause empty and update off inside the loop body after the read (e.g. for (off = 0; off < sizeof(rand_data); ) { len = read(...); ... off += (size_t)len; }).
